nodes.title: Workflow Parameters
widgets_values:
Parameter |Description |
-|-|
Input Path | The location of your input files.
Project Name | Output files will be placed in a directory with this name in your ComfyUI output directory.|
Index | **Set this to 0 for each run** unless you have a specific reason to use a different value. Controls which file is processed each time the workflow runs. Automatically increments on each run. |
Replace Frames | The number of frames to regenerate on each side of the stitch. e.g. If set to 8, then VACE will generate 16 frames; 8 frames at the end of video1 and 8 frames at the start of video2. This is the number of frames that will be *overwritten* by newly generated frames. Start small, 4 or 8 frames and adjust upward until you like the result.
Context Frames | The number of frames before and after the transition that VACE will use as starting points for frame interpolation. 8 is a good value to start with.
Add Frames | The number of additional frames to generate in addition to *Replace Frames*. Effectively extending the videos from the middle. The same rules apply here as with regular Wan generations, so going over 81 total generated frames (*Replace + Context + Add*) can lead to looping motion. I haven't found this to be terribly useful, but maybe you will. If you have a reason to set *Replace Frames* to zero, then you'll want to add some frames here. I usually keep it at 0.

nodes.title: Join and Save
widgets_values:
* ***Join and Save*** is a convenience feature for quickly stitching together the output from ***Generate***. 
   - You can also use your favorite video join/interpolate/upscale workflow or video editing app to accomplish this faster and better.
   - It doesn't scale well. You may run out system RAM if you try to join too many clips. In my case (128GB), ~200 clips is too many.

- You can run one or the other, not both together. ***Join and Save*** won't wait for ***Generate*** to complete before it tries to start doing its thing.

# If your input videos are using a framerate other than 16fps, you must manually set *frame_rate* in the Video Combine node here.
 FPS is handled correctly in the VACE generations, but this join process can't easily detect the input framerate so you must set it.

nodes.title: Index - reset this to 0 before running
How To Use This Workflow
widgets_values:
# How to Use This Workflow
## The purpose of this workflow is to generate transition frames between two or more input videos.
### This smooths out sudden motion shifts between clips and replaces noisy frames that sometimes appear at clip endings.

---
## IMPORTANT: Before running this workflow, you must configure it for your system. What works for my system probably doesn't work for yours. Pain and sorrow await if you do not read all the words and act accordingly.
---

**1. Ensure that model and sampler settings are correct for your environment.** Open the sampler subgraph and make any changes you require or desire for your environment. The default setup uses Wan 2.2 Fun VACE models and a standard two KSamplers. There are  alternative model/sampler setups provided as examples if you want something different. Models are loaded inside the sampler subgraph, so open that up too and confirm that the models, loras and optimizations are appropriate.

**2. Clean up from previous runs.**
- **Set the index parameter to 0.** If you forget this, the generations won't begin with the first video in your input directory. If the value of index is greater than the number of videos in your input directory, you'll see an error like *"sequence item 1: expected str instance, NoneType found."* Learn to recognize this as a reminder to reset index to 0.
- **Delete or rename existing vace-work directory.** If you're re-running, don't leave previous work files in your project directory or you'll have duplicate clips and that won't make a very good final video.

**3. Prepare inputs.** Your input videos should be placed in an empty directory and named such that they'll sort in the order they're meant to be viewed. e.g. video1.mp4, video2.mp4, etc.

**4. Set the workflow parameters.** See below for more detail on parameters.

**5. Set the batch count value (the number next to the blue Run button) to one less than the number of videos to be processed, and click Run.**

**6. Join the outputs together.** When processing is complete, outputs from this workflow will be written to a directory called *vace-work* under the *Project Name* directory. Join them together with your favorite video editing software (recommended!) or enable the *Join and Save* group in this workflow and do it that way. *Join and Save* only needs to run once, so be sure to set your Batch Count back to 1 before you start.

nodes.title: vace frames
widgets_values:
- *vace frames* = (*replace_frames* * 2) **gray frames. One set of** *replace_frames* **from the end of video1, one set of** *replace_frames* **from the start of video2.**

  - Gray *(8355711 decimal / 7F7F7F hex)* frames indicate that these frames will be generated.

nodes.title: VACE Control Mask
widgets_values:
### Black frames (value 0) in the VACE control mask indicate existing frames. White frames are those that VACE should generate.

With this mask, we are telling VACE we want to generate *replace_frames* number of frames from the end of video1, and also *replace_frames* number of frames from the start of video2. The model will interpolate these frames from the existing frames (black) in the input clips.

nodes.title: vace2
widgets_values:
* *vace2* = **The first** (*frame_overlap* * 2) **frames from input video2.**
  - **The first** *replace_frames* **frames are thrown away. These will be regenerated by VACE.**

  - **The following** *context_frames* + *replace_frames* **frames become the last third of the VACE control video.**

nodes.title: vace1
widgets_values:
- *vace1* = **The last** (*context_frames* + *replace_frames*) **frames from video1.**
  - The first (*context_frames* + 1) frames become the first part of the VACE control video.
  - The +1 is because Wan likes to generate 4n+1 frames at a time. *context_frames* is divisible by 4. +1 completes the magic formula.
  - The following *replace_frames* frames are thrown away. These will be regenerated by VACE.

widgets_values:
# - Build VACE control video from input video context frames and generated gray frames.
# - Build VACE control mask from empty black and white frames.

nodes.title: First Input File?
widgets_values:
If this is any video other than the first one in the batch, we remove the first (*context + replace*) frames from the video, since they were processed and saved in the previous run of the batch, when video1 was video2.

If we are processing the very first video in the batch (index==0), then we skip this split operation.

nodes.title: Split Input Videos
widgets_values:
# - Isolate the frames from the input videos that are needed for VACE generation.
# - Save frames from the input videos that are not needed for VACE generation.

nodes.title: Results of Split Input Videos
widgets_values:
- *clip1* = **The first** *frame_count* - (*context_frames* + *replace_frames*) **frames from video1.**
  - Saved immediately. Not used for frame generation.

* *vace1* = **The last** (*context_frames* + *replace_frames*) **frames from video1.**
  * These frames will be further divided in **Make VACE Controls**.

- *vace2* = **The first** (*replace_frames* + *context_frames*) **frames from video2.**
  - These frames will be further divided in **Make VACE Controls**.

* *clip3* = **The last** *frame_count* - (*context_frames* + *replace_frames*) **frames from video2.**
  - Not used for frame generation.
  - Usually discarded, to be processed in the next iteration.
  - Saved immediately if video2 is the final video in the batch.

nodes.title: Last Input File?
widgets_values:
If the is_last_file flag is set, save the remaining frames of video2.

Otherwise, we discard the remaining frames. They will be processed in the next iteration, when video2 will be video1.

Output video will be written with the same framerate as that of video1.
